Fig. 5
A showed the fluorescence emission spectra of 0.5μgmL−1 CDs@Eu-DPA MOFs in the presence of Cu2+ with different concentration (0.05, 0.1, 0.2, 0.4, 0.6, 0.8, 1, 2, 4, 6, 8, 10μM). The fluorescence intensity of CDs@Eu-DPA MOFs at 615nm decreased gradually with the increasing of the Cu2+ concentration, while the fluorescence intensity at 425nm was basically maintained. The F425/F615 linearly varied as the Cu2+ concentration with a wide linear range from 0.05μM to 10μM and a low detection limit of 26.3nM (S/N=3) (Fig. 5B). The detection limit of 26.3nM was much lower than the maximum allowable concentration of the US Environmental Protection Agency (20μM) and the World Health Organization (30μM) in drinking water. The performance of the proposed ratiometric fluorescence sensor based on CDs@Eu-DPA MOFs was superior to some others Cu2+ sensors (Table 1
). The good performance might result from uniform ball-flower-like nanostructures of CDs@Eu-DPA MOFs, which resulted in a large number of Eu-DPA MOFs to react with Cu2+.
